JavaScript Temporal.Duration:

- A Temporal.Duration represents a length of time.
- It can include years, months, weeks, days, hours, minutes, seconds, and more.


#) Duration Formats:
    - Duration objects can be parsed as a string using the ISO 8601 duration format.
    - It has the following form (spaces are only for readability):
        +P nY nM nW nD T nH nM nS
    -üí° for eg, For example, "P3Y6M4DT12H30M5S" represents a duration of "three years, six months,
        four days, twelve hours, thirty minutes, and five seconds".

        Code	Description
    ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        +	    Optional +/- sign for positive/negative duration. Default is +.
        P	    Duration designator (for period)
        nY	    Number of calendar years
        nM	    Number of calendar months
        nW	    Number of weeks
        nD	    Number of calendar days
        T	    Time designator (precedes time components)
        nH	    Number of hours
        nM	    Number of minutes
        nS	    Number of seconds


#) Create a Duration:
    - 1Ô∏è‚É£ You can create a Duration using an object
            const duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 7, hours: 2 }); // P7DT2H
    
    - 2Ô∏è‚É£ You can create a Duration using numeric values.
        In this example, the duration is 7 days:
            const duration = new Temporal.Duration(0, 0, 0, 7); // P7D

        ->üí° The parameters represent:
            Years
            Months
            Weeks
            Days
            Hours
            Minutes
            Seconds
            Milliseconds
            Microseconds
            Nanoseconds


#) Add and subtract a Duration:
    - You can add a Duration to a date or date-time.
    - You can subtract a Duration using the subtract() method.
    - üí°The original value does not change.
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-02-17");
            const duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 7 });
            const result = date.add(duration);                      // 2026-02-24

            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-02-17");
            const duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 7 });
            const result = date.subtract(duration);                 // 2026-02-10


#) Calculate the Difference Between Two Dates:
    - You can calculate the duration between two dates using until() or since().
    1Ô∏è‚É£ since():
        - The since() method calculates the duration between two temporal date/time values.
        - ‚ö†Ô∏èThe since() method is effectively the inverse of the until() method.
        - Syntax: temporal.since(temporal, options)
        - The since() method returns a Temporal.Duration Object representing the elapsed time.
        - ‚ö†Ô∏è The duration is positive if the "other" date is in the past, or negative if it is in the
            future. eg:
            const wedding = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();
            const duration = today.since(wedding);      // -P80D (-80 days)
        
        - The since() method returns the total number of days, but you can use the largestUnit option
            to break it down into years and months:

            const wedding = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();
            const duration = today.since(wedding, {largestUnit:'years'});   // -P2M21D (0 year, -2 month, -32 days)
    
    2Ô∏è‚É£ until():
        - The until() method calculates the duration between two temporal date/time values.
        - The until() method is effectively the inverse of the since() method.
        - Syntax: temporal.until(temporal, options)
            const wedding = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();
            const duration = today.until(wedding);      // P80D 

            const wedding = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();
            const duration = today.until(wedding,  { largestUnit: 'years' });   // P2M21D   

            const start = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-01");
            const end = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17");
            const difference = start.until(end);        // P16D

        - ‚ö†Ô∏èThe since() method does this - other.
        - ‚ö†Ô∏èThe until() method does other - this.


#) Duration vs Date Math:
    - With Date, you often calculate time differences manually using milliseconds.
            const start = new Date("2026-05-01");
            const end = new Date("2026-05-17");
            const diff = end - start;               // 1382400000
    
    - Temporal provides built-in methods that are clearer and safer.


#) When to Use Duration
    üëâ Adding or subtracting time.
    üëâ Calculating age.
    üëâ Measuring differences between dates.
    üëâ Working with time spans (hours, days, months).